  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Preventing and Responding to GBV-Uganda and South Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Levels of poverty and violence against women and children are high in both the isolated rural area of Nkomazi, in Mpumalanga, South Africa, and also in Karamoja, in North Eastern Uganda, where the people are largely cattle-herders, in transition to living in settled communities.  Services are scarce, and cultural norms prevent women from speaking out when they suffer violence.   This project will establish relationships, including with the male traditional leaders, to encourage women to come forward, and also to change men&#x2019;s behaviour in the future.  The project will respond both to the immediate needs of women for accessible support services, including medical help, and also work with communities to address root factors that perpetuate violence, subordination and discrimination against women.  It will work with local leaders and duty bearers to increase public consciousness and increased responsiveness towards the safety, protection and well-being of survivors and women and girls at risk of violence. There will be cross-learning between the two implementing partners, which will lead to improved good practice.</narrative>
  </description>
